                     <interp inst="t18330411-185-person1381" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18330411-185-viclabel1046" type="occupation">captain in the army</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330411-185-victim1369 t18330411-185-viclabel1046"></join>, and <rs id="t18330411-185-viclabel1047" type="occupation">lieutenant in the Coldstream Guards</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330411-185-victim1371 t18330411-185-viclabel1047"></join>. The body of this draft is certainly the prisoner's writing; the signature I do not know - it is not my writing.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Is the name like your writing? A. It is certainly an imitation - I am adjutant of the regiment, and sign drafts for recruiting parties; I believe the person who wrote this 
               <persName id="t18330411-185-person1382">
                  James 
                  Compton
               <interp inst="t18330411-185-person1382" type="surname" value="Compton"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330411-185-person1382" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330411-185-person1382" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , wrote this James Hope.</p>
               <p>MR. COLLINS. I saw the prisoner write this 
               <persName id="t18330411-185-person1383">
                  James 
                  Compton
               <interp inst="t18330411-185-person1383" type="surname" value="Compton"></interp>
